1.1 Explanation of Specific Lines¶

  • Line 1 The symbols /$*$ and $*$/ enclose a block comment, which may extend over any number of lines
    EVERY well-written program should begin with a large block comment specifying the name of the file, the author of the program, when it was written, and a brief description of what the program does and why. In large projects the opening comment may include reference to external documents ( software requirements documentation ), and may include a revision history of who modified the program when and for what purposes.
  • Line 7 The #include statement informs the compiler of what libraries are needed.
    • stdio.h contains the definitions of standard input and output functions. It is very rare that a C program would not need this header file.
    • //, indicates a comment that extends to the end of the current line.
  • Line 9 says that we are starting a function named main, which is the starting point for all C programs.
    • The keyword int says that main returns an integer value as its return type. ( See line 16. )
    • The open brace indicates the beginning of a block of code, which must be matched by a closing brace ( on line 17. )
  • Line 13 "printf" is the standard library function for formatted printing
    • Any data can be output to standard output (stdout), the console display screen
    • A simple text string can be enclosed in double quotes, as shown
    • The \n indicates a new line character. Without this, all the printout would appear on a single line. Multiple \n characters yield blank lines.
    • Note the semicolon at the end of the line, which is how C knows that a statement has ended.
  • line 16 Every function must have a return statement, which causes the function to end and return control to whoever called it.
    • Because main was declared to have an integer return type in line 9, this function must return an integer.

1.2 How to compile and run a standard c program¶

All C language tools need to compile C code ( a file with extension .c) and assemble it. Further, they need to link this assembled code with other assembled modules and libraries in order to create a finished executable program.

  1. Using IDE(integrated development environment), including a text editor. e. g. XCode, VScode + c compiler extension
  2. Terminal/DOS Shell
    • gcc -o runme zb1-5-1.c
    • ./runme
  3. Jupyter C kernel integrated in Jupyter notebook
  4. Online compiler, for example: Online C Compiler or Tutorialspoint

1.3 Comments and whitespace¶

ref: ZB1.6, 1.10

A comment is text a programmer adds to code, to be read by humans to better understand the code but ignored by the compiler. Two common kinds of comments exist:

  • A single-line comment starts with // and includes all the following text on that line. Single-line comments commonly appear after a statement on the same line.
  • A multi-line comment starts with /$*$ and ends with $*$/, where all text between /$*$ and $*$/ is part of the comment. A multi-line comment is also known as a block comment.

Whitespace refers to blank spaces (space and tab characters) between items within a statement and blank lines between statements (called newlines). A compiler ignores most whitespace.

good practice¶

make a program more readable

  • Use blank lines to separate conceptually distinct statements.
  • Indent lines the same amount.
  • Align items to reduce visual clutter.
  • Use a single space before and after any operators like =, +, , or / to make statements more readable.

2.1 printf()¶

  • The printf() function is used to print output from a program.
    • printf() allows a program to print text along with formatted numbers and text.
    • To use the printf() function, a program must include the stdio library using the statement #include <stdio.h>.
    • The first argument to the printf() function is a format string. The format string defines the format of the text that will be printed along with any number of placeholders, known as format specifiers, for printing numeric values and text stored in variables. It can specify %s, %d, %c, %f, etc., to print or read strings, integer, character or float respectively.
    • see zyBook 2.20, The detailed formating I/O
    • if we want to print a newline character, we use '\n'
  • Example: zyBook 1.5.1, zyBook 1.5.3
In [20]:
// Example 1
#include <stdio.h>

int main(void) {
   
    int wage; // variable declaration
    wage = 20; // variable assignment
    
    char name[] = "Joe";
   
    printf("name: %s\n",name);
   // printf("%s\n", name);
    
    
    printf("wage is %d", wage);
    //printf("%d", wage);
    printf("\n");
    printf("%s's wage is %d",name, wage );
    
 
   return 0;
}

name: Joe
wage is 20
Joe's wage is %20

2.2 scanf()¶

  • The scanf() function can be used to read a user-entered value into a variable. (see zyBook 1.5.3: A program can get an input value from the keyboard.)
    • Similar to printf(), the first argument to scanf() is a format string that specifies the type of value to read. Thus, scanf("%d", &age); will read a decimal integer from the user input.
    • For each format specifier in the format string, scanf() must include a corresponding argument. The & before the variable name age indicates the location or address in memory of the variable, where scanf() will store the read value.
    • scanf() can also read a string into a character array, using %s. However, no & precedes the character array argument.
    • The example scanf("%s", name); illustrates will read a string (or character arrar) from the user input , and store the values to variable name. must not be used when reading a string.
    • A common error when trying to read a user-entered string (a character array) using scanf is to place an & before the string variable.
    • Similarly, a common error when using scanf to read a numeric or character data type is to forget the & before the variable name.
#include <stdio.h>

int main(void) 
{
    char name[100]; int age;
    printf( "Enter your name :");
    scanf("%s", name); 
    printf("Enter your age:");
    scanf("%d",&age);
    printf( "Your name is %s, and you are %d years old\n", name, age); 
    printf("\nEnter your name and age:");
    scanf("%s %d", name, &age); 
    printf("Name: %s, Age: %d",name, age); 
    return 0;
}

Enter your name : James
Enter your age: 21
Your name is James, and you are 21 years old

Enter your name and age:Bond 38
Name: Bond, Age: 38

note for scanf():¶

  1. scanf() expect input in the same format as you provided %s and %d, which means you have to provide valid input like "string integer", if you provide "string string" or "integer integer" then it will be assumed as wrong input.
  2. while reading a string, scanf() stops reading as soon as it encounters a space so "this is test" are three strings for scanf().

3.1 Variables¶

  • A variable is a name given to a location in memory where a value can be stored, and can be referred to in other places of the program.
  • A variable has to be declared before it is used (declaration)(see zyBook 1.5.1 and zyBook 2.2.1)
  • A variable is for a specific type (data type)
  • Assign a value to a variable before using it for some other purpose, such as printing or having its value assigned to another variable. (assignment)

  • Value can change during program execution (updating)

  • Give variables valid names follow certain rules

3.1.1 Variable declaration¶

  • General form for declaring a variable is: < data_type > < variable_name_list >;
  • For example :
    • char letter;
    • int i,j;
    • float x = 0.4;

3.2.2 Variable Assignment¶

  • < variable > = < expr >
  • When assigning values, we put the variable to be assigned to on the left hand side (LHS), while the value to plug in on the RHS. LHS and RHS are connected by an equal sign (=), meaning assignment.

  • Assign a value to a variable before using it for some other purpose, such as printing or having its value assigned to another variable. (assignment)

3.2.3 Updating variable value:¶

  • A variable takes different values at different times.
  • Can hold only one value
    • Whenever a new value is placed into a variable, the new value replaces the previous value.
In [22]:
// Example 4
#include <stdio.h>

int main(void) {
    
    /* declare 3 integers
    int x;
    int y; 
    int z;
    */
    int x, y, z; //declare 3 integers
    
    /* variable assignment */
    x = 5; // assignment
    //assign y using another variable (must hold value already)
    y = x;
    printf("x = %d y = %d\n", x, y);
    
    /*can you do the following ?
    y = z; // z is not initiated by the user, so will have random integer
    printf("x = %d y = %d\n", x, y);
    */
    z = x + 2; //x+2 is expression (evaluaed as integer 7)
    printf("x = %d y = %d z = %d\n", x, y,z);
    
    //can you do this?
    //x + y = 10; //invalid 
    
    /*updating variable's value */
    x = 3;
    printf("updating x: x = %d y = %d z = %d\n", x, y,z);
    
    //updating variable's value
    y = y * 5;
    z = z + 5; // z += 5; 
    printf("updating y: x = %d y = %d z = %d\n", x, y,z);
    return 0;
}

x = 5 y = 5
x = 5 y = 5 z = 7
updating x: x = 3 y = 5 z = 7
updating y: x = 3 y = 25 z = 12

3.3 Identifiers and Naming Rule¶

see zyBook2.3

A C identifier is a name used to identify a variable, function, or any other user-defined item.

Naming convention¶

There are two commonly used style in programming for compound words:

  1. camelCase or lowerCamelCase
  2. snake_case or lower_case_with_underscore

C Naming policy¶

  1. All variables should be meaningful, long enough to give me a clue as to what they do in a program, but short enough as representative
  2. Every variable must begin with a alphabet or underscore (_), followed by any sequence of alphabet, digits, or underscores!
  3. variables are case sensitive.
  4. C names use camelCase
  5. cannot be keyword or pre-written functions (e.g. delay() in Arduino C), see Arduino functions

Keywords¶

Keywords(also called ‘Reserved words’) are the words that have specific and predefined meaning in the C programming language. All keywords are lowercased.

3.4 Expressions¶

see zyBook2.4

An expression is created by combining operands and operators. For example

  • a + b
  • b * 5
  • 15 > num2
  • operands: can be
    • a variable(e.g. a, b) ,
    • a literal (constant value, e.g. 5, 'A', "James"). A notation for representing a fixed value in source code. Its value cannot be changed as a program runs. Literals are often used to initialize variables. For example, the text was contained inside double quotation marks.
    • a constant (e.g. PI)
  • operators: arithmatic operators(+, -, *, /, %, ++ ), relational operators (>, <, <=, ==), or logical operators (&&, ||, !), etc.
    • unary operators(e.g. ! , ++) and binary operators (+, *, <=, = )
    • more details about operators and precedence see zybook Table2.4.2: Precedence rules for arithmetic operators.C operators
  • for example: x = a + b $*$ 5; here, x is assigned 35 if a holds 5 and b holds 6 , not 55 because operator has a higher precedence than +, so it first gets multiplied with 65 and then adds into 5.

3.4.1 Arithmetic Operators¶

Following table shows all the arithmetic operators supported by C language. Assume variable A holds 10 and variable B holds 20, then:

Notes: the - operator is also for negation, as in -x + y, or x + -y.

In [10]:
#include <stdio.h>
int main() 
{
    int a = 25; 
    int b = 10; int c ;
    printf("a = %d, b = %d\n", a, b);
    
    
    
    c = a + b;
    printf("c = a + b - Value of c is %d\n", c );
    c = a - b;
    printf("c = a - b - Value of c is %d\n", c ); 
    c = a * b;
    printf("c = a * b - Value of c is %d\n", c );
    c = a / b;
    printf("c = a / b - Value of c is %d\n", c ); 
    
    c = a % b;
    printf("c = a %% b - Value of c is %d\n", c );
    
    a++; 
    b--;
    printf("after a++, b--: a = %d, b = %d\n", a, b);
    ++a; 
    --b;
    printf("after ++a, --b: a = %d, b = %d\n", a, b);
    
    //FYI:
    c = a++; // c = a; then a++
    printf("c = a++ : Value of c is %d, a is %d \n", c,a ); 
    c = a--;
    printf("c = a-- : Value of c is %d, a is %d \n", c,a );
    
    c = ++a; //  a++, then assign to c 
    printf("c = ++a : Value of c is %d, a is %d \n", c, a );
    c = --a;
    printf("c = --a : Value of c is %d, a is %d \n", c,a );
   
   
    return 0;
}

a = 25, b = 10
c = a + b - Value of c is 35
c = a - b - Value of c is 15
c = a * b - Value of c is 250
c = a / b - Value of c is 2
c = a % b - Value of c is 5
after a++, b--: a = 26, b = 9
after ++a, --b: a = 27, b = 8
c = a++ : Value of c is 27, a is 28 
c = a-- : Value of c is 28, a is 27 
c = ++a : Value of c is 28, a is 28 
c = --a : Value of c is 27, a is 27

//Example 5
#include <stdio.h>

int main(void) {
    
    char nameOfSchool[] = "CofC"; //variable declaration and assignment
    int numOfStudent = 10000; //variable declaration and assignment
    
    /*increase number of student by 1000 */
    
    //numOfStudent = numOfStudent + 1000;
    //using compound operators 
    numOfStudent +=   1000; // numOfStudent = numOfStudent + 1000;
    
    printf("After one year, the numer of students in %s is %d\n", nameOfSchool, numOfStudent);
    
    /*declare integer x, y, z */
    int x , y, z ; //multiple variables declaration in one statement
    x = 1, y = 1, z = 1; //variable initialization/assignment in one statement
    x += 6; // x = x + 6;
    y /= 5; // y = y / 5;
    z *= 5; // z = z * 5;

    printf("x = %d, y = %d, z = %d \n", x, y, z);
 
  return 0;
}

After one year, the numer of students in CofC is 12000
x = 7, y = 0, z = 5

3.4 Constant¶

see zyBook2.9

Constants are like a variable, except that their value never changes during execution once defined. Using keyword const to define

const <datatype> <constant name> = <fixed value>

For example

In [3]:
// Example constant
# include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    const int LED_BUILTIN = 13;
    const float PI = 3.1415926;
    printf("LED_BUILTIN = %d, PI = %f", LED_BUILTIN, PI);
}

LED_BUILTIN = 13, PI = 3.141593

Another way to define a constant is using

#define LED_BUILTIN 13
  • #define is a preprocessor directive.
  • Things defined by #define are replaced by the preprocessor before compilation begins.

3.6 Statements¶

C is an imperative language based on. That is, programs in C consists of lines composed of statements. A statement can be:

3.6.1. Simple Statement¶

 - an assignment(simple & compound assignment)
 - a function call

Each line of a C code ending with ;

In [23]:
/* simple statement example  example6.c 
By Dr. Xu
This program is for explaining the building blocks of C
*/

# include <stdio.h>    //For accessing the standard library functions

int main() {
    /*  literals: "James", 3.14, 5, 6, PI, '!'
        Variables: a, b, name, c, punc
        Constant: PI 
        Expressions: a + 6, a + b * 3, 
        function: printf
        datatype: char, int, float
    */
        
    int a, b;    //variable declaration ;
    a = 5;       // variable assignment 
    b = a + 6;   // variable assignment
    int c = a + b * 3;     //variable declaration and initialization
    const float PI = 3.14; // define a constant with float datatype 
    printf("a = %d, b = %d\na + b * 3 = %d, PI = %f\n", a, b, a + b * 3, PI ); //function call
    char name[] = "James";  // double quotes for string
    char punc = '!';        // single quotes for character
    
    printf("Good bye, %s %c \n", name, punc);
    return 0;
}

a = 5, b = 11
a + b * 3 = 38, PI = 3.140000
Good bye, James !

Above for loop executes the

  1. initialization loop variable, i = 0, only once; at the very beginning of the statement.
  2. check the loop's condition, i < 5, before each time through the loop, if the condition is true, go to step 3, if the conditon is false, go to step 5
  3. executes the loop body printf("Welcome!\n");
  4. update loop variable : i ++, at end of each time through loop, then go to step 2
  5. end of loop

for loop (will be covered later)¶

for loop:

  • A type of loop in which the number of times the statements in a loop run is numerically defined.

  • It used to execute a set of programming statements multiple times

  • The for loop statement itself has three parts. Each places a role in setting up and running a logical test that determines how many times the statements are executed.

    • initial condition,
    • the test,
    • the increment.

Eventually the programming statements in increment will create a situation where the test no lon- ger evaluates to true. When this happens, the programming statements within the curly braces are no longer executed, and the program will move to what comes after the for loop.

Function block¶

  • Function is a group of statements that together perform a task.
  • Every C program has at least one function, which is main(), and all the most trivial programs can define additional functions.
  • You can divide up your code into separate functions.
    • How you divide up your code among different functions is up to you, but logically the division usually is so each function performs a specific task.
  • A function declaration tells the compiler about a function's name, return type, and parameters.
  • A function definition provides the actual body of the function.
  • A function is known with various names like a method or a sub-routine or a procedure, etc.
  • The detailed of function will be covered in chapter 6
  • Case1: if your function defination is written after the caller(where you call the function), you have to put the function declaration before the caller, usually we put all function declarations at the beginning of the code,
    • or make another hearder file funcs.h, then add #include <funcs.h> in the beginning of the code
  • Case2: if your function defination is written before the caller, you can omit the function declaration statement

4. Write simple program¶

4.1. The Software Development Process¶

The process of creating a program is often broken down into stages according to the information that is produced in each phase

  • also see the example from textbook chapter 2 pp.28 for Arduino program

Six Steps of the software development process.

  1. Analyze the problem
  2. Determine the specification (inputs, outputs and how are they related)(IPO)
  3. Create a design (algorithm/pseudocode)
  4. Implement the design
  5. Test/debug the program
  6. Maintain the program

4.2 Example:¶

  • calculate the area of a circle

4.2.1 Analize the problem¶

Figure out exactly the problem to be solved. Try to understand it as much as possible.

Ans:

  • circleArea: calcuate the area of a circle given the radius

4.2.2 Determine specifications¶

Describe exactly what your program will do.

  • Don’t worry about how the program will work, but what it will do.
  • Includes describing the inputs, outputs, and how they relate to one another.

circleArea:Ans:

  • Input: radius
  • Output: area
  • Process: Output = input x input x PI

4.2.3 Create a Design¶

  • Formulate the overall structure of the program. This is where the how of the program gets worked out.
  • Develop your own algorithm that meets the specifications. (A step-by-step set of instructions for accomplishing some task is called a algorithm)
  • the algorithm is writen in pseudocode, which is just precise English that describes what a program does.
  • the simple algorithm can follows a standard pattern: Input, Process, Output (IPO).

circleArea Pseudocode:

  • Input : receive the input from user and store the value to a variable radius
  • Process calculate area by using the formula: $A = \pi r^2)$
  • Output display area on the screen

4.2.4 Implement the Design¶

  • Translate the design into a computer language. (C)
    • What are the variables to use, and what is the data type for each variable
    • plug in the pseudocode as the comments

#include <stdio.h>

int main(){
    // display the purpose of the program
    printf("The program is to calculate the area of a circle with radius given by the user.\n") ;
   
    // define the variable: radius and area, both with datatype float
    float radius, area;
    
    // input: receive radius from the user (keyboard) 
    printf("Enter the radius of a circle:");
    scanf("%f", &radius);

    // process: Calculate area by using the formula of a circle
    area = 3.1415926 * radius * radius; 
    
    // output: display the `area` on the screen
    printf("The area of a circle with radius %f is %f.\n", radius,area);  
    
    return 0;
}

4.2.5 Test/Debug the program¶

  • Try out your program to see if it worked. If there are any errors (bugs), they need to be located and fixed. This process is called debugging.
  • Your goal is to find errors, so try everything that might “break” your program!

4.2.6 Maintain the program¶

  • improve
  • add file name, author name, purpose of the problem statement, edition number, etc.
In [ ]:
/* circleArea.c
by Dr. Xu
The program is to calculate the area of a circle with radius given by the user
*/

#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
int main(){
    // display the purpose of the program
    printf("The program is to calculate the area of a circle with radius given by the user.\n") ;
   
    // define the variable: radius and area, both with datatype float
    float radius, area;
    const float PI = 3.1415926;
    // input: receive radius from the user (keyboard) 
    printf("Enter the radius of a circle:");
    scanf("%f", &radius);

    // process: Calculate area by using the formula of a circle
    area = PI * pow(radius, 2); 
    
    // output: display the `area` on the screen
    printf("The area of a circle with radius %f is %f.\n", radius,area);  
    
    return 0;
}

4.3 Exercise:¶

  • Temperature Conversion (Celsius to Fahrenheit)
  1. Analyze the problem
    • C2F: the temperature is given in Celsius, user wants it expressed in degrees Fahrenheit

  2. Determine the specification (inputs, outputs and how are they related)(IPO)

    • Input – temperature in Celsius
    • Output – temperature in Fahrenheit
    • Process: Output = 9/5(input) + 32

  3. Create a design (algorithm/pseudocode) IPO

    • Input: receive the input from the user (keyboard) the temperature in degrees Celsius (call it celsius)
    • Process: Calculate fahrenheit by using the formula: $F = \frac{9}{5}C + 32$
    • Output: display the fahrenheit on the screen

  4. Implement the design
